>At first I was thinking you are doing an excessive amount of fear mongering but then I read this sentence
>&quot;I bet that at least one of your fellow students will wind up in a psychiatric hospital.&quot;
>I knew two students in my Ph.D. program in math who ended up  in a psychiatric ward.<p>Sorry, but this is also anecdotal fear-mongering. I just graduated with a PhD in CS, currently doing a postdoc, and do you know the number of people in my program who ended up in a psychiatric ward? None.<p>So, what does this tell us? Nothing. These are anecdotes. They give you at best a sample size of ~50 people, and a highly biased one at that.<p>I agree that we need to share both positive and negative stories from PhD programs (and honestly, I&#x27;ve seen plenty of both sorts posted to HN – the stories being told are not as uniformly rosy as the GP claims), but maybe we need to supplement these with an actual accounting of the risks and outcomes of a PhD in a given field, rather than ghost stories and fairy tales.
